(tgt_ref_freq <- ref_freq[1])
## [1] 160
tdat <- dat %>% 
  filter(ref_freq == tgt_ref_freq)

reversalfilterselect rev_dat group_byoccur

# pull out reversal data 
rev_dat <- tdat %>%
  filter(reversal == 1) %>%
  select(sub, ref_freq, ref_amp, test_amp, test_freq, trial_id) %>%
  arrange(sub, ref_freq, ref_amp, test_amp, trial_id)

# count the reversals
# for each subject and condition
rev_dat <- rev_dat %>%
  group_by(sub, ref_freq, test_amp) %>% # for each condition 
  mutate(occur = row_number())

# Confirmatory data analysis
# the effect of amp. on judgement
#
# logistic regression
# generalized linear mixed effects models
# base model
m1 <- glmer(correct ~  d_freq + d_amp + d_freq:d_amp +
        + (1|sub) 
        + (-1+d_freq|sub)
        + (-1+d_amp|sub),
        data = tdat,
        family = binomial,
        na.action = "na.fail",
        control = glmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))
summary(m1)

# model comparison with reduced models
# AIC: akaike's information criteria
# i=AICiAICmin,
#  where AICi is the AIC of the i-th model, and AICmin is the lowest AIC one obtains among the set of models examined (i.e., the prefered model). 
#
# The rule of thumb, outlined e.g. in Burnham & Anderson 2004, is:
#   if i<2, then there is substantial support for the i-th model (or the evidence against it is worth only a bare mention), 
#            and the proposition that it is a proper description is highly probable;
# if 2<i<4, then there is strong support for the i-th model;
# if 4<i<7, then there is considerably less support for the i-th model;
# models with i>10 have essentially no support.
# https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2004-20150-004
dredge(m1)
